# Project Rules

## File Structure
- Jekyll-based project structure
- Assets organized in dedicated folders (/assets/js/, /assets/css/, /assets/img/, etc.)
- Sass partials in _sass directory
- Data files in _data directory
- Includes in _includes directory

## Coding Standards

### HTML
- Use semantic HTML5 elements
- Maintain proper indentation (2 spaces)
- Use double quotes for attributes
- Include descriptive alt text for images
- Follow BEM naming convention for classes

### CSS/SCSS
- Follow BEM methodology
- Use variables for colors ($color-1, $color-2, etc.)
- Use mixins for media queries
- Maintain modular SCSS structure
- Use clamp() for responsive typography
- Follow mobile-first approach
- Use standardized spacing units (24px, 48px, 60px)

### JavaScript
- Use ES6+ syntax
- Use const/let instead of var
- Follow camelCase naming convention
- Use descriptive variable names
- Implement IntersectionObserver for animations

### Jekyll
- Use front matter for page metadata
- Organize data in _data directory using JSON format
- Use includes for reusable components
- Follow Jekyll's naming conventions for files and directories

### Performance
- Optimize images and media files
- Implement lazy loading where appropriate
- Minify CSS and JavaScript in production
- Use appropriate image formats (SVG for icons, WebP/JPEG for photos)

### Accessibility
- Maintain proper heading hierarchy
- Ensure sufficient color contrast
- Include ARIA labels where necessary
- Ensure keyboard navigation support

### Version Control
- Use meaningful commit messages
- Follow Git branch naming conventions
- Keep commits focused and atomic
- Document major changes in readme.md

### Documentation
- Include setup instructions
- Document dependencies and requirements
- Comment complex code sections

### Browser Support
- Support modern browsers
- Implement graceful degradation
- Use appropriate vendor prefixes
- Test across multiple devices and browsers

